Thus, we have $\sin\angle XOY=\frac{a}{b}+\frac{d}{c}$ and $\cos\angle XOY=\sqrt{1-\sin^2\angle XOY}=\sqrt{1-\left(\frac{a}{b}+\frac{d}{c}\right)^2}$. Therefore, the area of the sector $OXY$ is $\frac{1}{2}b^2\arcsin\left(\frac{a}{b}+\frac{d}{c}\right)$ and the area of the sector $OZY$ is $\frac{1}{2}c^2\arcsin\left(\frac{a}{b}+\frac{d}{c}\right)$. Thus, the area of the annulus is \begin{align*}
\pi b^2-\pi c^2+\frac{1}{2}be+\frac{1}{2}cd-\frac{1}{2}b^2\arcsin\left(\frac{a}{b}+\frac{d}{c}\right)-\frac{1}{2}c^2\arcsin\left(\frac{a}{b}+\frac{d}{c}\right) &=\boxed{\pi(b^2-c^2)+\frac{1}{2}be+\frac{1}{2}cd-\frac{1}{2}(b^2-c^2)\arcsin\left(\frac{a}{b}+\frac{d}{c}\right)}.
\end{align*}

The area of the annulus is the area of the larger circle minus the area of the smaller circle.  The area of the larger circle is $\pi b^2$, and the area of the smaller circle is $\pi c^2$.  Hence, the area of the annulus is $\pi(b^2-c^2)$.

