Then $C = \left( \frac{1 + 11}{2}, \frac{-5 + 7}{2} \right) = (6,1),$ and $D = \left( \frac{11 + x}{2}, \frac{7 + y}{2} \right),$ where $(x,y)$ is the intersection of the diagonals.

Since $CD$ is the average of $\overrightarrow{AB}$ and $\overrightarrow{0},$
\[D = C + \frac{1}{2} \overrightarrow{AB} = (6,1) + \frac{1}{2} \overrightarrow{AB}.\]Also, $BD$ is the average of $\overrightarrow{AC}$ and $\overrightarrow{AB},$
\[D = B + \frac{1}{2} \overrightarrow{AC} = (11,7) + \frac{1}{2} \overrightarrow{AC}.\]Hence,
\[(6,1) + \frac{1}{2} \overrightarrow{AB} = (11,7) + \frac{1}{2} \overrightarrow{AC}.\]Then $\overrightarrow{AC} = \overrightarrow{AB} + 2 \overrightarrow{CD},$ so
\[\overrightarrow{AC} = \langle 11 - 1, 7 - (-5) \rangle + 2 \left\langle \frac{11 - 1}{2} - 6, \frac{7 - (-5)}{2} - 1 \right\rangle = \langle 10, 12 \rangle.\]Hence,
\[D = (11,7) + \frac{1}{2} \langle 10, 12 \rangle = \boxed{(16,13)}.\]

